The paper presents a streaming algorithm for counting hypergraphs in a distributed setting, which suggests that it belongs to the category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The algorithm also deals with edge-insertions and edge-deletions, which indicates that it may be relevant to the sub-category of discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The paper also introduces a family of graph polynomials for the hypergraph counting problem, which suggests that it may be relevant to the sub-category of computational complexity (cs.CC). Additionally, the paper's focus on data streams and distributed settings may make it relevant to the sub-category of social and information networks (cs.SI) and the sub-category of information theory (cs.IT).
